	<td bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >One way to try and mitigate the effects of distance is to root the mob and have both toons back up a bit and stand right next to each other. /Assist the mobs and see who has aggro. I <i>think</i> that once you get out of melee range, distance doesn't play as dramatic of a role <i>comparitively</i>. <br />
<br />
You could also move the toons closer and farther away and see how much space it takes to get the mob to switch targets.<br />
<br />
I've had a theory for a while about absolute hate and effective hate, which I've talked about here before. We don't know if the taunt skill works off of effective hate or absolute hate. You could test that also by using 2 warriors and a cleric. Have the cleric stun multiple times with the "Stun" spell (cheap, no damage). Have warrior 1 taunt the mob from the cleric until he gets aggro. Root the mob, have both the warrior and cleric back up a decent distance from the mob. Now have warrior2 go up and taunt the mob <i>while the warrior and the cleric are some distance away</i>. Have everyone move to the same distance away from the mob, /assist to find which player is the mobs target. If taunt works off of effective hate instead of absolute hate, warrior2 will not be the target when he is the same distance from the mob as warrior1.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >__________________<br>
