<a href="showthread.php?postid=22434#post22434"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Post #87</font></a><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Registered: May 2003<br>
	Posts: 226<br><br>



	Server: Fennin Ro<br>





                Guild: <br>



<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=491143&resize=true" target=_blank>Magelo Link</font></a>

<br>	
</td>
	<td bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >FYI guys this is a brillant thread.<br />
<br />
<blockquote><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >quote:</font><hr>Any chance that the Taunt skill could add 10,000hate on a success, or agro+1, whichever is lower? The amount of hate added would have to be fairly high, high enough so in most cases a successful Taunt should put you at agro+1 anyways. But the Taunt skill will never actually put you higher than agro+1, that's why more successful Taunts without anyone actually going higher on the list than you first do nothing (only Taunt when you DON'T have agro). This explains Brutal's latest test. He never did more than just get on the agro list with a successful Taunt (agro+1)...no one else was on it, and he never did one point of damage. Taunt will never give enough agro to go higher than agro+1, obviously, so all those successful taunts never added agro because the equation can't give more than agro+1, which he was already at.<hr></blockquote> <br />
<br />
Putting on my technical hat I'd say this has a pile of merit.  I would expect that they implemented this in a similar way to other processes.  I mean knowing what we know about where Verant was 3 years ago would they have had time/money to develop complex logic?  No they would have stuck to a similar design.  I also think they went with the simplest design possible that yielded the highest performance in terms of throughput.  I think that is described up above.<br />
<br />
<br />
If what has been stated above is true (darn nice work Bruutal) I think that server logic calculates +/- agro values and complies them onto an aggregate "agro bucket" database value.   It does this fairly inelegantly so as not to cause performance issues.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Concept: "Agro Decay"</b> <br />
If "agro decay" (the idea that agro fades over time) exists then:<br />
<br />
1. The bucket gets dumped periodically (very possible if data is cached for performance reasons)<br />
2. The bucket gets reset (i.e values older than X stop going into aggregate "or sum" logic for the "agro bucket value")<br />
<br />
Thinking that performance was their #1 concern I'm guessing its option 1.<br />
<br />
<b>Taunt "Spaghetti"</b> <br />
<br />
Was just brainstorming all the agro/taunt changes since day 1.<br />
- Proximity changed<br />
- Agro given to procs changed<br />
- Actual taunt skill changed<br />
- Addition of EB weapons (direct hate add) added<br />
- DA chars removed from agro list<br />
- Facing agro changed<br />
- Spell agro changed<br />
- Addition of AE taunt<br />
- Tuning of AE taunt<br />
- Changing of how root agro works<br />
<br />
etc all.  Just something additional to chew on.  As hard as folks have worked on pareses its only as good as the soundness of the logic below it.  I think the 4  taunt-Agro thing is an artifact of a bug.  Just my opinion mind you ;-)<br />
<br />
<b>Regarding the experiment</b> <br />
<br />
You've gotten a pile of armchair quarterbacking but have you considered facing agro (i.e run experiement with you and cleric on opposite sides).  Proximity and facing agro != the same thing.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
